Oral and Maxillofacial Tumor Management - From Biopsy to Surgical Removal.

Castejón-González AC(1), Reiter AM(2).

Author information:
(1)Department of Clinical Sciences and Advanced Medicine, School of Veterinary 
Medicine, University of Pennsylvania, 3900 Delancey Street, Philadelphia, PA 
19104, USA.
(2)Department of Clinical Sciences and Advanced Medicine, School of Veterinary 
Medicine, University of Pennsylvania, 3900 Delancey Street, Philadelphia, PA 
19104, USA. Electronic address: reiter@vet.upenn.edu.

The main objective of oral and maxillofacial (OMF) tumor resection is to get 
local control of the disease. Many OMF tumors can be cured with wide or radical 
surgery, whereas others might only achieve temporary local control of the 
disease by removing infection and the source of pain, thereby improving the 
quality of life of the patient while keeping masticatory function. The standard 
of care on managing OMF tumors includes the diagnosis and identification of the 
local and distant extension of the disease to establish an appropriate treatment 
plan tailored for each patient. In this article, we provide a practical review 
of the current information related to staging, biopsy, and main surgical 
techniques for OMF tumor removal.

